00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:28.330
So the connect table.

00:23:28.330 --> 00:23:30.510
So we talked about the
challenge of connecting,

00:23:30.510 --> 00:23:32.343
and we had some really
interesting examples,

00:23:32.343 --> 00:23:34.880
particularly in online
or very large courses,

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:39.140
or folks who are doing part-time
learning where you can never

00:23:39.140 --> 00:23:41.865
gauge who's in the room
or why they're there.

00:23:41.865 --> 00:23:44.240
So we had a lot of discussions
about different techniques

00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:44.930
to try.

00:23:44.930 --> 00:23:47.210
And something
interesting is to make

00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:50.000
them feel a connection to
you as the instructor, which

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:53.144
is a kind of strange thing
maybe in an online setting

00:23:53.144 --> 00:23:54.560
to feel like you
can take the time

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:56.300
to try to get the
students to know you

00:23:56.300 --> 00:23:59.030
and to understand that you're
not there just to make this

00:23:59.030 --> 00:24:02.760
difficult for them, but that
you are motivated to help them.

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:04.550
So we talked about that.

00:24:04.550 --> 00:24:06.500
We talked about some
challenges in connecting

00:24:06.500 --> 00:24:10.970
in courses that are actually
really hard because sometimes

00:24:10.970 --> 00:24:14.762
they'll think that you're just
in it to embarrass them or give

00:24:14.762 --> 00:24:16.220
them a terrible
grade or something.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:17.690
And we talked about
the importance

00:24:17.690 --> 00:24:19.460
of sort of setting
that vision upfront,

00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:22.560
even taking the time,
especially in the beginning,

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:25.380
to make that connection
to their bigger picture.

00:24:25.380 --> 00:24:26.270
Why are they there?

00:24:26.270 --> 00:24:28.430
What-- this is going
to be a long journey,

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:29.570
but go on it with me.

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:32.060
And then trying to reiterate
that message a few times

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:33.630
throughout the semester.

00:24:33.630 --> 00:24:35.300
And then a great
tip at the very end

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:37.310
of the semester, once
hopefully they've

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:40.610
done that journey with you,
to ask if they could offer

00:24:40.610 --> 00:24:41.720
words of advice or wisdom.

00:24:41.720 --> 00:24:45.020
What did they wish they knew
at the beginning of the course?

00:24:45.020 --> 00:24:47.750
And then having that available
in your pocket for when

00:24:47.750 --> 00:24:49.430
you teach it the next
time because it's

00:24:49.430 --> 00:24:54.014
coming from other students,
not from scary you.

00:24:54.014 --> 00:24:55.430
And then we just
talked in general

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:59.430
about the concept of fostering
participation and engagement,

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:02.370
which we felt is really
important to connection.

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:04.430
And again, that's
establishing what

00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:06.974
I know in the business school
we call a learning contract

00:25:06.974 --> 00:25:09.140
upfront, just letting them
know that what you expect

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.575
preparation being
very essential,

00:25:11.575 --> 00:25:13.950
as is participation, and that
the more that they do that,

00:25:13.950 --> 00:25:15.460
the more they'll get out of it.

00:25:15.460 --> 00:25:19.510
And trying as best you can
to create a safe environment,

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:21.969
just to make sure that people
feel comfortable speaking up.

00:25:21.969 --> 00:25:23.135
That's what we talked about.

00:25:23.135 --> 00:25:23.640
Great.

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:25.765
I love that one of the many
ideas you said in there

00:25:25.765 --> 00:25:28.400
is the idea of connecting
even between classes

00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:29.414
of different years.

00:25:29.414 --> 00:25:30.830
So there's connections
that can go

00:25:30.830 --> 00:25:32.538
in so many different
directions, but even

00:25:32.538 --> 00:25:35.240
that longitudinal,
institutional knowledge.

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:36.930
That's a great idea.

00:25:36.930 --> 00:25:39.376
So the last principle, assess.

00:25:39.376 --> 00:25:41.000
And this is assessing
our own teaching,

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.300
not assessing the
student's learning.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:48.350
But so anyone who'd be
comfortable sharing out?

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:51.290
I don't know that we did such a
good job tackling the assessing

00:25:51.290 --> 00:25:54.980
because we ended up touching
on all these other issues, too,

00:25:54.980 --> 00:25:57.740
but all because
of the challenges

00:25:57.740 --> 00:25:59.240
of figuring out how to assess.

00:25:59.240 --> 00:26:01.160
And so we didn't come
up with solutions.

00:26:01.160 --> 00:26:04.370
We had a couple of
ideas which were having

00:26:04.370 --> 00:26:08.600
in-class polling that
can be showing live,

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:12.620
so you get a sense of,
basically, is this working?

00:26:12.620 --> 00:26:15.980
And identifying problems
before moving on past them.

00:26:15.980 --> 00:26:20.630
We talked about not being
too adherent to student

00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:23.060
evaluations, but having--

00:26:23.060 --> 00:26:24.820
going back to the
aims, which is like,

00:26:24.820 --> 00:26:26.060
this all kind of
comes full circle.

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:27.740
But going back to the
aims and thinking,

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:30.170
you know, how can we
figure out five years out

00:26:30.170 --> 00:26:32.030
whether they know it or not?

00:26:32.030 --> 00:26:33.680
And is there a way
we can implement

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:37.070
that to reach out to people
and find out what they know?

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:41.780
And then finally, we talked
about the value of small groups

00:26:41.780 --> 00:26:45.530
within the class with guided
questions as a way of you

00:26:45.530 --> 00:26:48.190
can figure out what
they knew coming in,

00:26:48.190 --> 00:26:52.020
and they can teach each other
within that small group,

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:56.250
and that also empowers them
to speak up within the class.

00:26:56.250 --> 00:26:59.790
So I think those are the
main things that we covered.

00:26:59.790 --> 00:27:00.640
Yeah.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:04.850
But what we all agreed on is
that there is not a good way

00:27:04.850 --> 00:27:08.060
to assess as far as
we can tell right now.

00:27:08.060 --> 00:27:09.580
And if you guys
have other thoughts,

00:27:09.580 --> 00:27:12.305
that would be really
helpful to everyone.

00:27:12.305 --> 00:27:14.160
That's great.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:14.660
Let's see.

00:27:14.660 --> 00:27:16.520
In terms of other
thoughts on assess.

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:19.070
I mean, I am struck
by the last point

00:27:19.070 --> 00:27:21.320
you made of, sort
of, if we're trying

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:23.090
to assess the efficacy
of our teaching,

00:27:23.090 --> 00:27:24.200
assessing our
students' learning.

00:27:24.200 --> 00:27:25.670
If you actually get
them in groups and see,

00:27:25.670 --> 00:27:28.040
can they do the tasks that
we're asking them to do?

00:27:28.040 --> 00:27:30.450
That is really good
real time feedback.

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:32.300
In addition to a
polling of, you know,

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:33.700
does this make sense to you?

00:27:33.700 --> 00:27:36.206
Or actually can you
do this question?

00:27:36.206 --> 00:27:39.260
But I mean, one thing I've seen,
and I'll circle back to this

00:27:39.260 --> 00:27:41.330
and see if my colleagues
have other thoughts,

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:44.960
but I'm hearing in a
really good productive way

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:47.540
the difficulty of
isolating these principles

00:27:47.540 --> 00:27:48.974
from each other.

00:27:48.974 --> 00:27:50.390
In the same way,
one of the things

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:52.190
that I have found
most powerful for me

00:27:52.190 --> 00:27:55.040
as I think about how to
tackle teaching problems,

00:27:55.040 --> 00:27:57.830
is the idea of having a
pedagogical repertoire,

00:27:57.830 --> 00:28:00.232
and then matching it
to the right situation.

00:28:00.232 --> 00:28:01.940
And in this case,
we're almost meta here.

00:28:01.940 --> 00:28:03.920
It's sort of we have a
teaching problem, a practice,

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:05.795
and we're trying to
figure out what principle

00:28:05.795 --> 00:28:07.640
can be sort of the
entry point, or, sort

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:09.710
of, the main lever for change.

00:28:09.710 --> 00:28:12.530
But they're all interconnected,
and so when we hear

00:28:12.530 --> 00:28:14.420
about people starting with--

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:15.920
being in activate
and realizing they

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:17.870
want to go back
towards aim, or people

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:20.810
who are doing things about
detect and seeing that trust

00:28:20.810 --> 00:28:22.520
and connecting is a
really important way

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:25.020
to be able to detect because
people aren't going to give you

00:28:25.020 --> 00:28:28.440
the data that you need if
they don't feel comfortable.

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:32.900
And so I feel like my last
thought on the assess question

00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:35.870
that you opened up
was it is a thing

00:28:35.870 --> 00:28:40.370
to start from the beginning as
a culture in the classroom, of I

00:28:40.370 --> 00:28:44.330
myself am very open to learning
from you and making changes,

00:28:44.330 --> 00:28:47.180
so it's the in-class polling,
it's the one-minute papers

00:28:47.180 --> 00:28:49.160
at the end of the
first class session,

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:52.310
it's the mid-semester feedback,
it's reporting it back to them

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:54.980
and then showing that
you're doing those changes.

00:28:54.980 --> 00:28:57.440
Such that-- because I
often read course evals

00:28:57.440 --> 00:28:59.900
and help faculty
members digest them,

00:28:59.900 --> 00:29:02.780
and it's not surprising,
but notable to me

00:29:02.780 --> 00:29:06.070
how many times students
say, this was an issue.

00:29:06.070 --> 00:29:10.100
The faculty got data from
us and really addressed it,

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:12.200
and I deeply
appreciate that, and we

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:15.560
saw how it changed over the
trajectory of the experience.

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:18.560
So that sort of building
assessment in on a daily basis

00:29:18.560 --> 00:29:20.374
has, to me, been
really powerful.

00:29:20.374 --> 00:29:22.040
I don't know if you
have anything to add

00:29:22.040 --> 00:29:23.731
on that before we transition.

00:29:23.731 --> 00:29:25.230
I think if I can
just add one thing.

00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:28.970
So I've been using anonymous
feedback surveys built

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:32.000
into Canvas, which are
basically a variation

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:33.210
on the minute paper.

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:36.020
And I've been doing it for
four years now, I think.

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:38.030
And I will never
teach without it

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:40.850
again because you learn so much.

00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:42.530
You think you can
assess how people

00:29:42.530 --> 00:29:44.420
are doing by looking
them in the eye,

00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:48.540
but when you actually ask
them, you learn things like,

00:29:48.540 --> 00:29:52.400
oh, this activity didn't go
well because it was too hard,

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:55.220
or because all of my
kids have the flu,

00:29:55.220 --> 00:29:57.080
and it was just a hard week.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:29:59.780
You get all of this
information from people

00:29:59.780 --> 00:30:03.170
that you wouldn't otherwise
get just by asking,

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:04.910
and it's wonderful.

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:07.070
So I highly, highly
recommend it.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:07.600
Yeah?

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:13.570
So I just-- we tried that
last year, and what we found

00:30:13.570 --> 00:30:19.796
was that all we did was invite
the angry people to anonymously

00:30:19.796 --> 00:30:22.280
tear us apart.

00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:24.860
And then people
started skipping it.

00:30:24.860 --> 00:30:28.820
And I actually ended up having
students come up after and say,

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:29.780
I'm not one of them.

00:30:29.780 --> 00:30:31.160
I'm on your side.

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:34.100
And so we decided not
to do it this year.

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:37.941
So, you know, I think
they can go both ways.

00:30:37.941 --> 00:30:38.440
It can.

00:30:38.440 --> 00:30:41.420
I make them worth
one point every week.

00:30:41.420 --> 00:30:44.480
I mean, that's silly, but
it does get people to do it.

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.070
And I also-- I report back
on it every single week.

00:30:47.070 --> 00:30:49.220
So I say, this many people--

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:51.960
half the group thought this
activity was fantastic,

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:53.690
the other half did not.

00:30:53.690 --> 00:30:56.840
And that reporting lets them
see that there are lots of sides

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:58.287
to every issue, so that if--

00:30:58.287 --> 00:30:59.120
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:03.470
You obviously don't make
people as angry as we do.

00:31:03.470 --> 00:31:05.214
We have a response here.

00:31:05.214 --> 00:31:07.130
The other thing that we
do to get around this,

00:31:07.130 --> 00:31:09.260
